FINDINGS: 3

### [P1] The seven-reviewer cap refills a removed slot with an extra conditional reviewer

The retained cap changes high-risk dispatch behavior and breaks the plan’s promised two-dispatch reduction.

Evidence:

- `skills/bee-reviewing/SKILL.md:51-56` now defines four parallel core reviewers.
- `skills/bee-reviewing/SKILL.md:30,62` retains a seven-reviewer parallel-wave cap and requires every matched conditional to spawn.
- `skills/bee-reviewing/references/reviewing-reference.md:43-44` says matched triggers cannot be skipped and overflow is folded only after reaching seven.
- Before this commit, `320c7eb^:skills/bee-reviewing/SKILL.md:57-58` had a parallel researcher and an after-wave synthesizer.
- `docs/history/learnings-pair-relocation/plan.md:42-43` promises two fewer dispatches per standard/high-risk feature.

Failure scenario: If three conditionals match, the old run dispatched four core reviewers, the researcher, two conditionals, then the synthesizer: eight dispatches. The new run dispatches four core plus three conditionals: seven. Only one dispatch is removed, and a conditional previously folded into a core reviewer now receives its own dispatch.

Smallest credible fix: Change the parallel-wave cap from seven to six at `skills/bee-reviewing/SKILL.md:30,62` and `skills/bee-reviewing/references/reviewing-reference.md:44`. This preserves the former maximum of two conditional dispatches and the promised reduction of two.

### [P1] Conditional reviewers have incompatible tier instructions

The primary skill assigns conditionals to the review slot, while its reference still assigns them to the generation tier.

Evidence:

- `skills/bee-reviewing/SKILL.md:60` says conditional reviewers use the same `review` slot.
- `skills/bee-reviewing/references/reviewing-reference.md:26` assigns specialists to the review slot.
- `skills/bee-reviewing/references/reviewing-reference.md:32` instead says conditionals use the “same generation tier.”

Failure scenario: An orchestrator following line 32 dispatches a reliability or migration reviewer on the generation model, while one following the primary skill uses the configured independent-review model.

Smallest credible fix: Replace “same generation tier” at `reviewing-reference.md:32` with “same review slot.”

### [P3] The synthesis rationale overstates the orchestrator’s model tier

Synthesis ownership is clear, but the new explanation incorrectly guarantees that the orchestrator is the strongest model in the wave.

Evidence:

- `skills/bee-reviewing/SKILL.md:60` makes the reviewer slot independently configurable, including Opus or an external CLI.
- `skills/bee-reviewing/SKILL.md:72` calls the orchestrator the strongest model in the wave.
- `README.md:237` permits advisor mode to run the session—and therefore its orchestrator—on the generation tier.
- `docs/history/learnings-pair-relocation/plan.md:30-35` gives the narrower preservation argument: the former synthesizer used the orchestrator’s model.

Failure scenario: In advisor mode, a generation-tier orchestrator can synthesize findings from Opus review-slot agents, contradicting the stated guarantee even though ownership remains followable.

Smallest credible fix: Replace the “strongest model” claim with the plan’s precise statement that the former synthesizer used the orchestrator’s model, so inline synthesis removes a hop without changing the model used.
